docs.abstract: For the first time in the city’s long history as a cultural wellspring, it is fertile ground for filmmakers like the writer-stars of “Blindspotting.” What took so long?
docs.snippet: For the first time in the city’s long history as a cultural wellspring, it is fertile ground for filmmakers like the writer-stars of “Blindspotting.” What took so long?
docs.lead_paragraph: OAKLAND, Calif. — Daveed Diggs and Rafael Casal stood squinting in the June sun, unsure what to make of the graffiti-covered walls of a Boys & Girls Club here. The bright blue building in front of them had been spotless just a few months earlier, when Mr. Casal and Mr. Diggs, both Oakland born and bred, had last seen it.

headline.main: Oakland in Their Bones, and in Their Films

docs.abstract: Aurore Valade’s bright and busy photographs show that resistance can be messy, joyful and sometimes lonely.
docs.snippet: Aurore Valade’s bright and busy photographs show that resistance can be messy, joyful and sometimes lonely.
docs.lead_paragraph: ARLES, France — We live in an age of anger, we are told. It might be more accurate to say that we live in an age of protest. Whether at the Women’s March or defending Black Lives Matter, the March for Our Lives or the rallies in France against the policies of President Emmanuel Macron, a willingness to go into the streets and shout is a defining characteristic of our era.

headline.main: Eye-Popping Portraits for an Age of Protest

docs.abstract: Written by and starring Daveed Diggs and Rafael Casal, the film struggles to balance its ambition as an entertainment with its social concerns.
docs.snippet: Written by and starring Daveed Diggs and Rafael Casal, the film struggles to balance its ambition as an entertainment with its social concerns.
docs.lead_paragraph: The opening credits of “Blindspotting” showcase the city of Oakland, Calif., in split-screen, offering two distinctive points of view. One side shows a vibrant multiracial culture living in a frequently beleaguered environment; the other a gentrifying city whose newest residents — young, white, start-up-happy, new-money types — seem eager to embrace the area’s “authenticity,” as long as their interactions with its longtime residents don’t involve any real discomfort.

headline.main: Review: ‘Blindspotting’ Walks a Tense Line in a Gentrifying Oakland
headline.print_headline: A Tale of Two Cities, Both of Them Oakland
